Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the C++ class that libpcapng ships (the example assumes the public class is called `pcapng::Reader` and that it provides an STL‑style iterator over objects of type `pcapng::Frame`).  

The binding consists of  

* **`pcapng.mli`** – the OCaml public interface (the only file a user of the library will see).  
* **`pcapng_stubs.cpp`** – the C‑C++ glue code that is compiled with the OCaml runtime.  (The file is a C++ source file because it needs to talk to the C++ library; the entry points are declared `extern "C"` so that the OCaml linker can find them.)  

Both files together are enough to build a static or shared library that can be linked into an OCaml program.  The code is heavily commented, explains the memory‑management strategy, and shows a tiny usage example at the end.

---  

## 1.  `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml interface  

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml bindings to libpcapng (C++ iterator over frames)

   The binding is deliberately tiny – it only exposes what a typical
   OCaml user needs:

   • open/close a pcapng file
   • walk the frames with a user supplied callback
   • optionally fetch the next frame manually (useful for testing)

   All heavy lifting (iteration, conversion, memory management) lives
   in the C++ stubs.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** An opaque handle for a pcapng file.  The value must be passed to the
    other functions; it is automatically freed by [close] (or by the GC
    finaliser). *)
type t

(** A single network frame.  The fields are deliberately simple so that
    they can be built without any external dependencies.  The [data]
    field is a mutable byte‑array (OCaml [bytes]) containing exactly
    [captured_len] bytes. *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec       : int64;   (** seconds since the Unix epoch *)
  ts_usec      : int;     (** micro‑seconds part of the timestamp *)
  captured_len : int;     (** number of bytes stored in the file *)
  original_len : int;     (** length of the original packet on the wire *)
  data         : bytes;   (** the raw packet bytes *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Failure msg] if the file
    cannot be opened or the underlying C++ constructor throws. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a previously opened file.  The call is idempotent: calling it
    twice is safe, and the OCaml garbage collector will also call it
    automatically via a finaliser. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Walk the whole file, calling [f] for every frame that the C++ iterator
    yields.  The callback runs in the same thread as the OCaml code, so
    it may allocate OCaml values, raise exceptions, etc.  If [f] raises,
    iteration stops and the exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Fetch the next frame from the iterator, if any.  Returns [None] when
    the iterator is exhausted.  The function is not required for normal
    use; it is provided mainly for testing and for users that prefer a
    pull‑based style. *)
val next : t -> frame option
```

