## 3.  How to compile and link  

Below is a minimal `Makefile` fragment that shows how to produce a static library
`libpcapng_ocaml.a` and an OCaml module `pcapng.cma` that can be used from
ordinary OCaml code.

```make
# ------------------------------------------------------------
#   Paths – adjust to your system
# ------------------------------------------------------------
OCAML_INC   = $(shell ocamlc -where)
PCAPNG_INC  = /usr/include/pcapng          # <-- where libpcapng.hpp lives
PCAPNG_LIB  = -lpcapng                    # link flag for the C++ library

# ------------------------------------------------------------
#   Build rules
# ------------------------------------------------------------
all: libpcapng_ocaml.a pcapng.cma

# C++ object file – must be compiled with a C++ compiler
pcapng_stubs.o: pcapng_stubs.cpp pcapng.hpp
	$(CXX) -I$(OCAML_INC) -I$(PCAPNG_INC) -c -O2 -Wall -fPIC $< -o $@

# Static library that contains the stub object (used by OCaml)
libpcapng_ocaml.a: pcapng_stubs.o
	ar rcs $@ $^

# OCaml interface file (generated from the .mli)
pcapng.cmi: pcapng.mli
	ocamlc -c $<

# OCaml compiled module – links the C++ static library
pcapng.cmo: pcapng.ml pcapng.cmi
	ocamlc -c $<

pcapng.cma: pcapng.cmo libpcapng_ocaml.a
	ocamlc -a -o $@ $< -cclib -lpcapng -cclib -L. -cclib -lpcapng_ocaml

clean:
	rm -f *.o *.a *.cmi *.cmo *.cma
```

> **Important** – the final link step (producing an executable) must also
> pass the C++ library flags (`-lpcapng` etc.) to the linker, otherwise you
> will get “undefined reference” errors.

