## 4.  Small usage example (OCaml side)

```ocaml
(* test_pcapng.ml *)
let () =
  let p = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  Printf.printf "Iterating over frames …\n";

  (* Example 1 – callback style (the one you asked for) *)
  Pcapng.iter p (fun fr ->
      Printf.printf "frame: ts=%Ld.%06d  cap_len=%d  orig_len=%d\n%!"
        fr.Pcapng.ts_sec fr.Pcapng.ts_usec fr.Pcapng.captured_len fr.Pcapng.original_len
    );

  (* Example 2 – pull style using [next] *)
  let rec dump () =
    match Pcapng.next p with
    | None -> ()
    | Some fr ->
        Printf.printf "next frame: %Ld.%06d\n%!"
          fr.Pcapng.ts_sec fr.Pcapng.ts_usec;
        dump ()
  in
  dump ();

  Pcapng.close p
```

Compile the test program:

```sh
ocamlc -I . -c pcapng.mli
ocamlc -I . -c pcapng.ml
ocamlc -I . -o test_pcapng \
       pcapng.cma test_pcapng.ml \
       -cclib -lpcapng -cclib -lpcapng_ocaml
```

Running `./test_pcapng` will walk the file, invoking your OCaml function
for each frame, exactly as requested.

---  

### What the binding does (in a nutshell)

| OCaml API | What the stub does |
|-----------|-------------------|
| `open_file` | Calls `pcapng::Reader` ctor, stores the pointer in a custom block. |
| `close` | Deletes the C++ object; also automatically called by the GC finaliser. |
| `iter` | Registers the OCaml callback as a global root, walks the C++ iterator, builds a fresh OCaml `frame` record for each C++ `Frame`, and calls the callback.  Exceptions from the callback or from C++ are propagated as OCaml failures. |
| `next` | Implements a simple pull‑based API using the (hypothetical) `has_next` / `next` methods of the C++ iterator.  Returns `None` when the iterator is exhausted. |

All memory that originates in C++ (`pcapng::Reader`, `pcapng::Frame`) is released
as soon as the OCaml handle is closed or garbage‑collected, so there are no leaks.
The only OCaml‑allocated data are the `frame` records (including the `bytes`
payload) that the stub creates on‑the‑fly; they are managed by the ordinary OCaml
GC.

Feel free to adapt the `pcapng::Reader` / `pcapng::Frame` names to the exact
API of the version of libpcapng you are using – the skeleton above works for
any iterator‑style C++ class that yields a struct containing the fields shown
in the `frame` record.
